content.explanation:
Original price of the commodity = Rs. p
And, new price of the commodity = Rs. q

Price of the commodity after the first increase of k% = p(100 + k)/100
Price of the commodity after the first decrease of k% = p{(100 + k)/100} × {(100 – k)/100}

Price of the commodity after the second increase of k% = p{(100 + k)/100} × {(100 – k)/100} × {(100 + k)/100}
q = Price of the commodity after the second decrease of k% = p{(100 + k)/100} × {(100 – k)/100} × {(100 + k)/100} × {(100 – k)/100}
Or q = p(100 + k) × (100 – k) × (100 + k) × (100 – k) / (100 × 100 × 100 × 100)
Or q = p[(100)² – k²] [(100)² – k²] / 10⁸
Or q × 10⁸ = p[(100)² – k²]²
Or q × 10⁸ = p[10⁴ – k²]²
